06:47.474 --> 06:49.774
[wes] you're the kind of
smooth-talker I like, okay?

06:49.777 --> 06:52.143
Because you deliver.

06:52.212 --> 06:54.079
-I like arlene's deal.
-Okay.

06:54.915 --> 07:01.420
And I would love to come in on
her deal, if she is interested?

07:01.488 --> 07:03.789
-Yeah, I would do that.
-There you go.

07:04.525 --> 07:05.423
Thank you, guys.

07:05.492 --> 07:06.892
I appreciate that.

07:07.394 --> 07:08.693
Do we have any other dragons?

07:11.231 --> 07:12.464
Michele?

07:13.299 --> 07:14.766
I think you have the best
possible deal on the table,

07:14.835 --> 07:15.901
So I'm gonna be out.

07:16.436 --> 07:17.469
There you go.

07:17.471 --> 07:18.970
Well, I appreciate it all,
dragons.

07:19.038 --> 07:21.739
Thank you for all of your input.

07:21.742 --> 07:24.709
-And, wes, arlene, let's do it.
-[arlene] that's awesome.

07:24.777 --> 07:25.810
[wes] done, congratulations.

07:25.813 --> 07:26.678
[chase] I'd definitely love to
take the deal.

07:26.746 --> 07:27.545
[arlene] congrats.

07:27.614 --> 07:28.679
[wes] okay, buddy,
congratulations.

07:28.749 --> 07:29.614
[chase] and just to celebrate,
it's definitely been

07:29.683 --> 07:31.783
A long drive, we better have a
cold one.

07:31.851 --> 07:33.351
-[dragons laugh]
-[chase] thank you, guys!

07:33.419 --> 07:34.319
[wes] good on you!

07:34.321 --> 07:35.520
-Take care!
-True canadian boy there!

07:35.588 --> 07:38.657
♪ ♪

07:40.059 --> 07:40.959
[arlene] it's crazy.

07:41.027 --> 07:42.727
I don't bet against people like
those men.

07:42.795 --> 07:44.095
I'm super excited.

07:44.164 --> 07:45.297
Thanks, guys.

07:45.766 --> 07:48.400
♪ ♪

07:49.036 --> 07:51.503
I can't do the--I mean, I could
do the deal...

07:51.571 --> 07:52.770
[manjit] don't.

07:52.839 --> 07:55.574
[vincenzo]...But I'd have to
take at least 45% for $200,000.

07:56.976 --> 07:58.643
I guess you must like crab
apples more than us.

07:59.512 --> 08:02.414
♪ ♪

08:04.952 --> 08:08.653
♪ ♪

08:12.458 --> 08:13.625
-[alex smyth] all right.
-[dianne] next:

08:13.627 --> 08:15.159
These ontario brothers think
their growing business is

08:15.228 --> 08:16.928
Ripe for the picking.

08:18.565 --> 08:19.464
Hello dragons.

08:19.533 --> 08:21.500
-My name is glen smyth.
-And I'm alex smyth.

08:21.568 --> 08:23.068
And we're the co-founders of
appleflats.

08:24.104 --> 08:25.871
We're the only company that's
commercializing crab apples.

08:26.740 --> 08:28.406
We started in 2016 with one
tree.

08:29.776 --> 08:31.276
We now harvest thousands of
trees making us the leader

08:31.344 --> 08:33.078
In restoring this species.

08:34.247 --> 08:35.747
We're from shakespeare,
ontario.

08:35.749 --> 08:38.383
We're looking for $200,000 for a
10% stake in our company.

08:40.554 --> 08:42.487
In the last 100 years, crab
apples have been in steep

08:42.489 --> 08:45.090
Decline and what we're offering
you today is an opportunity

08:45.158 --> 08:49.060
To save a species and bring a
new apple to a big market.

08:50.163 --> 08:51.663
Vince, if you could come down
and give us a hand,

08:51.731 --> 08:52.497
We're hoping--

08:52.499 --> 08:53.298
[wes] oh yeah.

08:53.366 --> 08:54.165
[michele] the farmer in the
group.

08:54.233 --> 08:55.232
[wes] the man.

08:55.302 --> 08:56.034
[arlene] you picked the most
sour guy on stage.

08:56.036 --> 08:57.535
-Yeah!
-[vincenzo] all right.

08:57.604 --> 08:59.904
[alex] this is our crab apple
sorting machine.

08:59.973 --> 09:02.373
These are obviously not crab
apples.

09:02.442 --> 09:03.975
Crab apples aren't in season
right now.

09:04.844 --> 09:09.180
This machine helps us sort the
fruit from the leaves

09:09.248 --> 09:10.281
And the sticks.

09:10.283 --> 09:12.984
We're gonna have you, vince,
do the old method.

09:13.053 --> 09:14.586
And voilà!

09:14.588 --> 09:15.720
What the hell is that?

09:15.789 --> 09:17.155
[alex] I'm gonna race you to see
which one's faster.

09:17.223 --> 09:18.957
You're gonna race me with the
machine, okay.

09:19.025 --> 09:20.825
-[alex] yes, so--
-my bet's on the machine.

09:20.894 --> 09:22.160
-[vincenzo] all right.
-[alex] ready?

09:22.228 --> 09:23.561
-[vincenzo] yeah, I'm ready.
-Go!

09:23.630 --> 09:26.364
[dianne] the brothers use this
machine for their urban harvest

09:26.433 --> 09:28.333
To collect crab apples from
homeowners' trees

09:28.401 --> 09:29.768
And city spaces.

09:30.537 --> 09:31.469
Come on, vince.

09:31.537 --> 09:32.437
You can do better.

09:32.439 --> 09:33.238
[alex] he is doing pretty good.

09:33.306 --> 09:34.271
[manjit] oh wow!

09:34.341 --> 09:35.206
[dianne] the harvested fruit is
then juiced,

09:35.275 --> 09:36.942
And later made into
crab apple products.

09:37.744 --> 09:40.578
[alex] so now basically think
about doing that for about

09:40.647 --> 09:44.949
125,000 pounds, and that's what
we were doing before we came up

09:45.018 --> 09:47.218
And patented this machine.

09:47.220 --> 09:48.686
And what is this next to us?

09:48.755 --> 09:49.854
So that's actually where we're
gonna go next.

09:49.922 --> 09:51.823
So as I mentioned, we do have
some products in market.

09:52.558 --> 09:54.258
We're knocking on the door of
600 stores.

09:54.327 --> 09:55.693
These are products that are
available.

09:55.696 --> 09:57.462
Feel free to enjoy them while
we're here.

09:58.564 --> 10:00.898
This is a traditional
pioneer-style crab apple jelly.

10:00.901 --> 10:03.768
We also make four different
flavours of crab apple

10:03.837 --> 10:05.103
Cocktail mix.

10:05.105 --> 10:06.037
[manjit] the juicy pear, it's
delicious.

10:06.106 --> 10:08.106
All it needs is a shot of vodka
[chuckles].

10:08.174 --> 10:09.641
How did you come up with this?

10:10.410 --> 10:12.543
Well, we basically always made
crab apple jelly

10:12.612 --> 10:14.446
As a family tradition.

10:14.514 --> 10:17.982
When glen was in university, we
decided to pick the entire tree

10:17.985 --> 10:21.019
At our front parent's place--

10:21.021 --> 10:23.721
And very quickly realized
there's no way we can eat

10:23.790 --> 10:28.559
All of this jam, so we called up
a local cheese shop, said,

10:28.562 --> 10:30.028
"hey, do you want
some of the this?"

10:30.096 --> 10:32.196
They said, "sure, we'll buy
everything you can have."

10:32.265 --> 10:33.932
Easiest $600 we ever made.

10:34.000 --> 10:35.800
And then three or four months
later, the cheese shop called us

10:35.868 --> 10:38.770
And said, "hey, can we buy more
crab apple jelly?"

10:38.838 --> 10:40.472
And my first reaction was,
"yeah, of course,"

10:40.540 --> 10:42.707
But it turns out
the answer is no.

10:42.775 --> 10:44.609
You actually can't go and
commercially buy

10:44.677 --> 10:45.943
Crab apples anymore.

10:45.946 --> 10:47.345
And that's actually what started
us down this whole path.

10:47.413 --> 10:48.913
Really?

10:48.981 --> 10:52.850
As apple growing and farming
just became more mechanized,

10:52.853 --> 10:57.355
It just became too hard to work
with these tiny, tiny apples.

10:57.357 --> 10:59.023
They go bad very quickly.

10:59.026 --> 11:03.461
Instead of like going and
harvesting and then taking it

11:03.463 --> 11:05.563
To the copacker, we juice and
freeze.

11:06.866 --> 11:08.600
And that juice doesn't degrade
over time.

11:08.668 --> 11:10.502
You're using food science to
your advantage.

11:10.570 --> 11:11.669
That's fantastic.

11:11.738 --> 11:15.206
So you guys hire people to go
pick the apples.

11:16.142 --> 11:18.710
And then do you guys pay for the
apples too?

11:18.778 --> 11:19.678
No.

11:19.746 --> 11:21.245
You will have to eventually pay
for the apples.

11:21.248 --> 11:22.380
I doubt it.

11:22.449 --> 11:23.581
People are just happy that
they're not going to waste.

11:23.650 --> 11:24.916
[manjit] not everybody is gonna
give you them for free.

11:24.918 --> 11:27.986
So it's sort a win-win for the
cities because they pay a ton

11:28.054 --> 11:30.422
To have their grounds crew clean
it up.

11:31.390 --> 11:33.624
-Clean up because they rot.
-[alex] and pests, like mice.

11:33.693 --> 11:36.127
So you think your costs of goods
for as long as you can see

11:36.129 --> 11:38.196
Are gonna be free,
it's just the labour?

11:38.198 --> 11:41.199
Yeah, we're only harvesting
about 30% to 40% of the capacity

11:41.267 --> 11:42.967
That we know of as of right now.

11:43.936 --> 11:47.171
That being said, we both looked
at that and said there's

11:47.240 --> 11:48.673
A serious cap on this.

11:48.741 --> 11:50.608
So as of four days ago, we've
planted the world's first

11:50.677 --> 11:53.411
High-density crab apple orchard
so we can actually transition

11:53.480 --> 11:56.781
From an urban harvest as our
primary source of apples into

11:56.850 --> 11:59.651
